@node a "Introduction"


 Introduction:

 
 The Amiga is an outdated, dead machine.
 
 People must be mad to continue clinging to an unsupported, non-standard
 platform such as the Amiga.
 
 This is how most people see the Amiga platform.
 
 What they never ask is @{b}why@{ub} Amiga owners still use their machines
 insatiably, even if they can afford to buy, outright, another machine.

 Why?
 
 Because the Amiga has a unique character, and this character is all to do
 with the way the Amiga works, its operating system.
 
 Let's make it clear, it is by no means perfect, it's incomplete, they've
 done a bunch of things wrong, but it has the seed, the potential, to become
 a lot better.
 
 If you conducted a survey regarding the most used operating systems on the
 planet today, I guarantee the results would show Windows and MacOS in first
 and second place respectively.
 
 The reasons are debatable, but most people use Windows because most people
 have PCs, which won over the Mac in the 70s and 80s as THE machine to have,
 basically because the Mac was too expensive, and had little software to
 start with, whereas the PC was cheaper and had more software available.
 
 The scenario was very similar to the BetaMax/VHS story, VHS won the war by
 sheer numbers, despite the fact that BetaMax was better quality.
 
 After using both operating systems for some time, it becomes clear which
 is better suited to which tasks, and where they are better than the Amigas
 operating system.
 
 The Mac isn't liked by technical people.
 This is because it's difficult to probe around and change things without
 the OS treating you like an idiot, and technical people become
 frustrated with this.
 
 Windows isn't liked by people who like the Mac because it's too messy
 to maintain, move a file and the whole thing falls over! Technically
 orientated people love this, because they can take pleasure in knowing
 that novice users don't understand how the whole thing works, and rely
 on technical people to help them out.
 
 You don't believe me? Okay, simple test, go into any bookshop, find the
 computing section, now look at the sheer number of books dedicated to
 helping people out with Windows (in fact anything written by Microsoft!)

 See! I told you so!
 
 So take the experimentation side of Windows, dilute it, add the way a
 Mac works, add true plug-and-play hardware, add pre-emptive multitasking,
 knock a third of the price (unless you're buying an A4000T!)  and there
 you have it, and Amiga 1200!
 
 So, what this all means is the Amigas OS hits an almost perfect balance
 between user-friendliness and power, so much in fact, that millions of
 people across the world won't part for anything else.
 
 I truly believe this is why the Amiga is still alive despite the total
 failure of several companies to do anything with it.
 
 If there is ever to be a PowerPC Amiga, it will be unrivalled in speed,
 because the Amigas OS is so lean, so efficient that nothing will come
 close to outpacing it.
 
 The only thing it needs is a severe face lift, and greater support for
 industry standards, then maybe some people might start developing for it.
 
 Thank you for listening...

