@node b "About this archive..."


 About this archive...
 

 This archive contains "screen shots" of how the interface might develop.
 There are some points I'd like to mention about the direction I chose
 when developing this archive.
 
 Firstly, I didn't want to blend Windows '95 with the MacOS like some
 other archives on the Aminet, because it's not true to the Amiga, do
 this and you lose what makes the Amiga the Amiga, personally I don't
 think there is anything inherently wrong with how the Amiga operating
 system "works", it's use of layered, pull down screens (something unique
 to how the Amiga) make it easy to use. It just needs some spit and
 polish here and there, and a few minor changes to some parts.
 
 That said, there are a few ideas that were taken from the other sources
 because they work so well, but more importantly, because they @{b}work
 well with the Amiga@{ub} something other archives don't take into
 account, the obvious example is using the Win'95 taskbar as an integral
 part of the AmigaOS, but not only is it obviously nicked from Windows,
 but it's very un-Amiga like.
 
 The look and feel of the AmigaOS has been carried across into the Cubic
 look, but with more detail added to the 3-Dimensional aspect of the
 interface, some parts have been re-drawn, for example the ability to
 add a resize gadget to a window without having to extend the borders
 all the way along the window.
 
 You may also think that it would look better with textures behind the
 buttons, windows, scroll bars etc. to make it look "really cool".
 From a practical point of view, this is @{b}bad GUI design@{ub} (MUI
 has a lot to answer for this!) It detracts from the information
 presented to the user and actually makes the interface less easy to
 use, which is where some people are mislead into thinking that MUI
 "makes programs easier to use" this is not true, and this is NOT
 the reason why MUI was developed, it was developed to make
 programming easier for the developer, and offer flexibility to the
 user, used correctly it WOULD make programs easier to use but most
 (not all) of the programmers who use MUI haven't got a clue when
 it comes to developing user interfaces that are well laid out, present
 the correct information at the correct time, offer a small learning
 curve by not cluttering the user interface etc.

 Cubic is designed to be easy to use, look professional and offer more
 options to the programmer. The ultimate goal would be to have
 consistent (for the user) looking programs that look the part, this
 is one of the problems with Amiga applications, they work well,
 are useful, but have childish, badly designed front-ends.
 
 A friend of mine once said that he thought the Amiga was a childs
 computer because it had big icons and a large mouse pointer! This
 is because he was looking at it in 320x256 lowres, and you know
 he was right.
 
 Obviously the Cubic look isn't going to be to everyones taste, but
 it offers a more practical direction than most of the attempts I
 have seen, and because it has a suite of screen shots it has one
 thing that others don't, consistency, none of these pie in the sky
 one off "drawings".
 
 Anyway, hope you enjoy it.
 
 
 Regards
 
 Matt.

